title: Cytoscape_Graphing
text: possible graph entire PCN, CFN, CCCNs entirety, though large graphs take long time graph. One approach navigating data structures select nodes large networks Cytoscape (R using RCy3::selectNodes()) select nearest neighbors shortest paths create subnetwork new window (see Cytoscape Manual https://manual.cytoscape.org/en/stable/). alternative approach described identify pathways, genes, PTMs interest R data objects, make smaller, interpretable graphs Cytoscape using RCy3. example, find names pathways Bioplanet contain EGFR. data object ‘pathways.list’ list, name list element name Bioplanet pathway element character vector genes pathway. want find interactions pathway “Transmembrane transport small molecules” pathways. utility functions used CytoscapeGraphing.R two versions PCN show cluster evidence Jaccard smilarity adjacent columns (first case) distinct edges (second case, can used plot network cytoscape). Let’s zero interactions proteins two pathways “EGF/EGFR signaling pathway” “Transmembrane transport small molecules” genes common, yet cluster evidence interaction strong. First extract network interactions genes two pathways. generate node file cytoscape. following case include data extracted ptmtable. optional, useful node size color used later indicate values data. function GraphCfn creates graph using cluster filtered network Cytoscape app. graphed, Cytoscape provides interactive interface view data. function requires edge list file (egfr_transporter.cfn example), node data file (egfr_transporter.nodes).
code: egfr_pathways <- names(pathways.list)[sapply(1:length(pathways.list),function(x){"EGFR" %in% pathways.list[[x]]})] length(egfr_pathways) #83 egfr_transporter.pcn <- filter.edges.between("Transmembrane transport of small molecules", egfr_pathways, PCNedgelist) egfr_transporter_pcn.cy <- filter.edges.between("Transmembrane transport of small molecules", egfr_pathways, pathway.crosstalk.network)  # head(egfr_transporter.pcn) egfr_transporter.cfn <- filter.edges.0(c(pathways.list[["EGF/EGFR signaling pathway"]], pathways.list[["Transmembrane transport of small molecules"]]), cfn) egfr_transporter.nodes <- make.cytoscape.node.file (egfr_transporter.cfn, funckey, ptmtable, include.gene.data = TRUE)

title: Using the P2P Package: A Step-by-Step Tutorial
text: MakeClusterList first step P2P process. function takes dataframe ptmtable runs three calculations statistical measures distance: Euclidean Distance, Spearman Dissimilarity (1- |Spearman Correlation|), SED (average Spearman Dissimilarity (1- Spearman Correlation) Euclidean Distance). Combining two dissimilarities leads better resolution data useful pattern recognition. correlation table— ptm.correlation.matrix—generated based distances calculated pair PTMs. function runs matrices t-SNE generate clusters based previously calculated distance provides cluster list, common.clusters. returned adj.consensus.matrix (identifies PTMs cluster together ‘short distance’ ) ptm.correlation.matrix also used next step create co-cluster correlation networks (CCCNs). three outputs returned list. keeplength paramter defines minimum number PTMs must cluster retained final output. toolong parameter defines maximum distance two PTMs considered clustering together. MakeClusterList can run like :    following unpacks output separate objects discussed : Now can view objects. First, example cluster: Next, look piece adjacency matrix. Ones represent pair cluster zeroes represent pair doesn’t: part PTM correlation matrix. code: fix.excel <- function(cell) {   fixgenes = c("CDC2", "1-Sep", "2-Sep", "3-Sep", "4-Sep", "5-Sep", "7-Sep", "8-Sep", "9-Sep", "10-Sep", "11-Sep", "15-Sep", "6-Sep", "1-Oct", "2-Oct", "3-Oct", "4-Oct", "6-Oct", "7-Oct", "11-Oct", "1-Mar", "2-Mar", "3-Mar", "4-Mar", "5-Mar", "6-Mar", "7-Mar", "8-Mar", "9-Mar", "10-Mar", "11-Mar", "C11orf58", 'C17orf57', 'C3orf10',  'C7orf51', "C11orf59", "C4orf16", "1-Dec", "14-Sep")   corrects = c("CDK1", "SEPT1", "SEPT2", "SEPT3", "SEPT4", "SEPT5", "SEPT7", "SEPT8", "SEPT9", "SEPT10", "SEPT11", "SEPT15", "SEPT6", "POU2F1", "POU2F2", "POU5F1", "POU5F1", "POU3F1", "POU3F2", "POU2F3", "MARCH1", "MARCH2", "MARCH3", "MARCH4", "MARCH5", "MARCH6", "MARCH7", "MARCH8", "MARCH9", "MARCH10", "MARCH11", "SMAP", "EFCAB13", "BRK1", "NYAP1", "LAMTOR1", 'AP1AR', "DEC1", "SEPT14")   cellv <- unlist(strsplit(as.character(cell), "; "))   if (any(fixgenes %in% cellv)) {     cellv.new <- gsub(fixgenes[fixgenes %in% cellv], corrects[fixgenes %in% cellv], cellv)     return (paste(cellv.new, collapse="; "))   } else return(cell)    } name.peptide <- function (genes, modification="p", sites, aa, pepsep=";")   {   genes.v <- unlist(strsplit(genes, pepsep, fixed = TRUE))   genes.v[which(genes.v == "NA")] <- NA   genes.v <- genes.v[!is.na(genes.v)]   sites.v <- unlist(strsplit(sites, pepsep, fixed = TRUE))   sites.v[which(sites.v == "NA")] <- NA   sites.v <- sites.v[!is.na(sites.v)]   sites.v <- sapply(sites.v, function (x) paste (aa, x, sep=""))   Peptide.v <- as.character(noquote(paste(genes.v[1:length(genes.v)], modification, sites.v[1:length(sites.v)], sep=" ")))   Peptide <- paste(unique(Peptide.v), collapse="; ")   return(Peptide) } file_path <- system.file("extdata", "phospho_cleaned_mapped.txt", package = "PTMsToPathways") # file_path <- "path/to/your/file.txt" newphos <- read.table(file_path, sep = "\t", skip = 0, header=TRUE, blank.lines.skip=T, fill=T, quote="\"", dec=".", comment.char = "", stringsAsFactors=F) dim(newphos) #> [1] 933 170 newphos <- newphos[!is.na(newphos$AllGeneSymbols),] dim(newphos) #> [1] 908 170 newphos$AllGeneSymbols <- sapply(newphos$AllGeneSymbols, fix.excel) headercols <- c("AllGeneSymbols", "Amino.Acid", "Positions.Within.Proteins", "Modification.Type") newphos.head <- newphos[,headercols] newphos.head$Peptide.Name <- mapply(name.peptide, genes=newphos.head$AllGeneSymbols, sites= newphos.head$Positions.Within.Proteins, aa=newphos.head$Amino.Acid)

code: phosdata <- newphos[,grep("Intensity", names(newphos))] phosdata <- phosdata[,grep("pTyr", names(phosdata))] names(phosdata) <- sapply(names(phosdata), function (x) unlist(strsplit(x, "Intensity."))[2]) zer0 <- which(phosdata==0, arr.ind = TRUE) phosdata <- replace (phosdata, zer0, NA) tr1.opt <- names(phosdata)[grep(".1", names(phosdata), fixed=TRUE)] tr2.opt <- names(phosdata)[grep(".2", names(phosdata), fixed=TRUE)] merge2cols <- function (colv1, colv2) {   newcolv=NA   if (is.na(colv1) & is.na(colv2)) {     newcolv=NA     return(newcolv)} else       if (is.na(colv1) | is.na(colv2)) {         newcolv <- sum(colv1, colv2, na.rm=TRUE)         return(newcolv) } else           newcolv <- (colv1 + colv2)/2         return(newcolv) }  # Use merge2cols() function to average technical replicates: phosdata.merged <- data.frame(matrix(nrow=nrow(phosdata), ncol=18)) for(i in 1:length(tr1.opt)) {   phosdata.merged[,i] <- mapply(merge2cols, colv1=as.numeric(phosdata[, tr1.opt[i]]), colv2=as.numeric(phosdata[,tr2.opt[i]])) } names(phosdata.merged) <- sapply(tr1.opt, function(x) substr(x, start=1, stop=nchar(x)-2)) phosdatafile <- cbind(newphos.head, phosdata.merged) write.table(phosdatafile, file="phosdatafile.txt", row.names = FALSE, sep="\t") rownames(phosdatafile) <- phosdatafile$Peptide.Name phosdata.df <- phosdatafile[,6:23] log2phosdata <- log2(phosdata.df) # ptmtable <- log2phosdata

title: Build Clusters Based on PTM Data Under Like Conditions — MakeClusterList
text: function takes post-translational modification table runs three calculations distance: Euclidean Distance, Spearman Dissimilarity (1 - |Spearman Correlation|), average two . calculations find 'distance' ptms based upon conditions occur. matricies run t-SNE order put 3-dimensional space. title: Build Clusters Based on PTM Data Under Like Conditions — MakeClusterList
text: ptmtable dataset post-translational modifications. Formatted row's names containing PTM names. column names drugs. Values numeric values represent much PTM reacted drug. keeplength keep clusters ptms whose size larger parameter. (.e keeplength = 2 keep ("AARS", "ARMS", "AGRS") ("AARS", "ARMS")); default 2 toolong numeric threshold cluster separation, defaults 3.5. tsne_perplexity perplexity parameter Rtsne. Please read Rtsne documentation information. tsne_max_iter Number iterations Rtsne. Please read Rtsne documentation information.

what: Graphing and Manipulating Cluster Filtered Network — getFuncKey
title: Graphing and Manipulating Cluster Filtered Network — getFuncKey
text: Creates cytoscape graph cluster filtered network. Ensure Cytoscape app open RCy3 package downloaded. package RCy3 required many functions script. download, run: (!require("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE)) install.packages("BiocManager") BiocManager::install("RCy3") also recommended (required) users load RCy3 library(RCy3) access functions directly.

title: Graphing and Manipulating Cluster Filtered Network — getFuncKey
code: getFuncKey(funckey.filename = "FunctionKey.txt")

title: Graphing and Manipulating Cluster Filtered Network — getFuncKey
text: cfn version ppi.network edges exist cccn.matrix non-zero weights ptmtable dataset post-translational modifications. Formatted numbered rows, first column containing PTM names. rest column names drugs. Values numeric values represent much PTM reacted drug. funckey table graphing gene names type protein; defaults internal database PTMsToPathways::ex.funckey Network.title Desired title created Cytoscape Network; defaults "cfn" Network.collection Desired name collection created Cytoscape network reside; defaults "PTMsToPathways" visual.style.name Desired name visual style created Cytoscape; defaults "PTMsToPathways.style" background.color Hex code background color graph; defaults '#fcf3cf' edge.label.color Hex code edge label color graph; defaults '#17202a' node.label.color Hex code node label color graph; defaults '#145a32' default.font Font style edge node names; defaults "Times New Roman" node.font.size Font size node name; defaults 12 edge.font.size Font size edge name; defaults 8 edge.line.style Type edge style; defaults "SOLID"; options include: "PARALLEL_LINES", "MARQUEE_EQUAL", "DOT", "EQUAL_DASH", "LONG_DASH", "CONTIGUOUS_ARROW", "MARQUEE_DASH", "DASH_DOT", "BACKWARD_SLASH", "FORWARD_SLASH", "VERTICAL_SLASH", "SOLID", "SEPARATE_ARROW", "MARQUEE_DASH_DOT", "ZIGZAG", "SINEWAVE" edge.opacity Opacity edge line scale 0 - 255 0 transparent; defaults 175 edge.label.opacity Opacity edge label scale 0 - 255 0 transparent; defaults 255 border.opacity Opacity node border scale 0 - 255 0 transparent; defaults 255 node.label.opacity Opacity node label scale 0 - 255 0 transparent; defaults 255 node.fill.opacity Opacity node fill scale 0 - 255 0 transparent; defaults 255

title: Extracts co-clustered PTM and gene network from a cluster filtered network object. — ptms_to_cfn
code: # Example input objects ptms <- c("TP53 p S15", "BRCA1 p S123; BRCA1 p T124", "MDM2 p S200") # Example network (edge list with 'source', 'target', and cluster info, could be data.frame or igraph) cfn.merged <- data.frame(source = c("TP53", "BRCA1", "BRCA1", "MDM2"),                          target = c("BRCA1", "MDM2", "TP53", "TP53"),                          cluster = c(1,1,2,1)) # Suppose filter.edges.0 and get.co.clustered.ptms are also defined and loaded # The following returns the gene/PTM subnetwork res <- ptms_to_cfn(ptms, cfn = cfn.merged, pepsep = ";") #> Error in ptms_to_cfn(ptms, cfn = cfn.merged, pepsep = ";"): object 'cfn.merged' not found print(res) #> Error: object 'res' not found
